<document><id>28687666</id><passage><infon key="type">title</infon><offset>0</offset><text>Domain-specific control of germ cell polarity and migration by multifunction Tre1 GPCR.</text><annotation id="0"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="77" length="9"/><text>Tre1 GPCR</text></annotation><annotation id="1"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="77" length="4"/><text>Tre1</text></annotation><annotation id="2"><infon key="code">222</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="82" length="4"/><text>GPCR</text></annotation></passage><passage><infon key="type">abstract</infon><offset>88</offset><text>The migration of primordial germ cells (PGCs) from their place of origin to the embryonic gonad is an essential reproductive feature in many animal species. In Drosophila melanogaster, a single G protein-coupled receptor, Trapped in endoderm 1 (Tre1), mediates germ cell polarization at the onset of active migration and directs subsequent migration of PGCs through the midgut primordium. How these different aspects of cell behavior are coordinated through a single receptor is not known. We demonstrate that two highly conserved domains, the E/N/DRY and NPxxY motifs, have overlapping and unique functions in Tre1. The Tre1-NRY domain via G protein signaling is required for reading and responding to guidance and survival cues controlled by the lipid phosphate phosphatases Wunen and Wunen2. In contrast, the Tre1-NPIIY domain has a separate role in Rho1- and E-cadherin-mediated polarization at the initiation stage independent of G protein signaling. We propose that this bifurcation of the Tre1 G protein-coupled receptor signaling response via G protein-dependent and independent branches enables distinct spatiotemporal regulation of germ cell migration.</text><annotation id="3"><infon key="code">222</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="282" length="26"/><text>G protein-coupled receptor</text></annotation><annotation id="4"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="310" length="21"/><text>Trapped in endoderm 1</text></annotation><annotation id="5"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="333" length="4"/><text>Tre1</text></annotation><annotation id="6"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="699" length="4"/><text>Tre1</text></annotation><annotation id="7"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="709" length="4"/><text>Tre1</text></annotation><annotation id="8"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">38765</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="729" length="9"/><text>G protein</text></annotation><annotation id="9"><infon key="code">222</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">35966</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="836" length="28"/><text>lipid phosphate phosphatases</text></annotation><annotation id="10"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">35966</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="865" length="5"/><text>Wunen</text></annotation><annotation id="11"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">53558</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="875" length="6"/><text>Wunen2</text></annotation><annotation id="12"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">140439</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="900" length="4"/><text>Tre1</text></annotation><annotation id="13"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">36775</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="941" length="4"/><text>Rho1</text></annotation><annotation id="14"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">37386</infon><infon key="type">Gen